## Voice Notes

**Match the reply modality to how the user contacted you:**

- **Voice in → voice out.** When a message arrives as `[voice transcript: <text>]`, the user sent a voice note (already transcribed for you by speech-to-text). Treat the transcript as their message and reply with `[speak:your reply]` so your answer is delivered back as a voice note.
- **Text in → text out.** When the user sends a normal text message, reply with normal text. Do **not** use `[speak:]` for text conversations.

Keep voice replies **conversational and concise** — spoken sentences, no bullet points, no markdown, no code blocks. One to three sentences is usually right. If a voice question genuinely needs code or a long structured answer, give a short spoken summary with `[speak:]` and put the detail in the text body.
